  <p>
    The phrase "international school" is used by almost every parent searching for education options in Jakarta. It is also used by dozens of schools to describe themselves. The two uses do not always match. Understanding the gap between the legal category and the educational reality helps families choose on substance rather than marketing.
  </p>

  <h2>The Regulatory Framework</h2>

  <p>
    In 2014, the Indonesian government brought all schools using foreign curricula under national oversight. Schools that had previously operated independently were required to register under a new structure. The most common route is the SPK licence, short for Satuan Pendidikan Kerjasama, which formalises a cooperation agreement between an Indonesian foundation and a foreign educational institution.
  </p>

  <p>
    SPK schools must meet Indonesian requirements around governance, staffing ratios, and the inclusion of certain national subjects. The framework creates accountability, but it does not define the quality or character of the education a school provides. That distinction sits at the centre of most parent confusion about the Jakarta school market.
  </p>

  <h2>Two Things the Label "International School" Can Mean</h2>

  <p>
    In practice, "international school" operates on two levels in Jakarta. The first is regulatory: how a school is licensed. The second is educational: what curriculum is taught, who teaches it, and what pathways it opens for pupils.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most schools that parents would consider genuinely international are SPK schools. But SPK is a licence, not a quality standard. Within the same regulatory category, schools range from deeply international in character to nominally so. Parents are better served evaluating the second level than the first.
  </p>

  <h2>What SPK Schools Look Like in Practice</h2>

  <p>
    SPK schools in Jakarta typically follow one of a small number of foreign curriculum models: the English National Curriculum, the International Baccalaureate, the American system with Advanced Placement options, or specialist frameworks such as Montessori in the early years. The SPK licence does not prescribe which of these a school uses. It also does not govern how consistently the curriculum is taught, how internationally experienced the teaching staff are, or the school's academic expectations.
  </p>

  <p>
    The compulsory Indonesian components required by the SPK framework cover subjects such as Bahasa Indonesia and Pancasila education. They sit alongside the main curriculum and do not alter the core qualification pathways. A pupil in an SPK school can still sit GCSEs, A-Levels, or the IB Diploma exactly as intended. The regulatory additions are not disruptive to the international programme.
  </p>

  <p>
    A common parental concern is that SPK status makes a school less international. In practice, SPK is the mechanism through which international schools legally operate in Indonesia. The label does not dilute the provision; it enables it.
  </p>

  <h2>Schools With International Elements</h2>

  <p>
    Alongside SPK schools, Jakarta has institutions that describe themselves as bilingual, national-plus, or offering international programmes. These are a different category. They follow the Indonesian national curriculum as the foundation, with international elements layered on top. These might include extended English instruction, foreign methodology such as Montessori or Cambridge frameworks, or international accreditation at the institutional level.
  </p>

  <p>
    These schools can be strong in their own right. But they are not built around a foreign qualification pathway. For families whose children may enter international senior schools, sit GCSEs or A-Levels, or move to a British, American, or IB school in another country, the distinction matters. A bilingual school following the Indonesian national curriculum does not offer the same academic continuity.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Look For Instead of the Label</h2>

  <p>
    The licensing category alone does not tell families what they need to know. More useful indicators include:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Curriculum depth.</strong> The school should deliver its chosen curriculum as intended, not as a selective blend. Ask which curriculum is followed and how consistently it is implemented across year groups.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Teacher qualifications.</strong> International curricula require teachers trained in those systems. A school delivering the English National Curriculum should employ teachers with UK Qualified Teacher Status or equivalent international experience. The proportion of overseas-trained staff is a reasonable proxy for the depth of international provision.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Accreditation and inspection.</strong> External validation from bodies such as CIS (Council of International Schools), COBIS (Council of British International Schools), or the IB Organisation gives a clearer picture of quality than any label. Accreditation reviews governance, safeguarding, curriculum delivery, and outcomes. Inspection reports, where available, are worth reading.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Qualification pathways.</strong> For families thinking beyond primary school, the curriculum foundation must lead to recognised qualifications. Jakarta currently has very few schools offering genuine GCSEs and A-Levels. The <a href="/insights/gcses-and-a-levels-guide">GCSEs and A-Levels guide</a> sets out what the pathway involves and which schools in the city offer it.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>School culture.</strong> Leadership style, classroom practice, and community mix all influence the experience more directly than the regulatory category. A school tour, a conversation with current parents, and a meeting with the head will reveal more than any marketing material.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions Worth Asking at Any School</h2>

  <p>
    When evaluating a Jakarta international school, these questions cut through the noise: Which curriculum does the school follow, and how is it assessed? What proportion of teachers have overseas training or international classroom experience? What does the school's inspection or accreditation record look like? What are the qualification outcomes for senior pupils? How are the compulsory Indonesian elements integrated without disrupting the core programme?
  </p>

  <p>
    Straightforward answers to these questions make it possible to compare schools on substance rather than on how they choose to describe themselves.
  </p>

  <p>
    Families weighing options across South Jakarta can use the <a href="/tools/school-comparison">ISJ school comparison tool</a> to compare curriculum models, fee ranges, and locations across the main international schools in the city.
  </p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>What does "international school" mean in Jakarta?</h3>
  <p>
    It is an informal term used by parents and schools to describe institutions delivering a foreign curriculum with international staffing. Legally, most operate under the SPK framework. The educational model matters more than the label.
  </p>

  <h3>What is an SPK school?</h3>
  <p>
    An SPK school is a formal cooperation between an Indonesian foundation and a foreign educational institution. It follows Indonesian regulations but delivers a recognised international curriculum. It is the main legal structure through which international-style schools operate in Indonesia.
  </p>

  <h3>Do SPK schools teach the Indonesian national curriculum?</h3>
  <p>
    No. They deliver a foreign curriculum but must include certain Indonesian subjects as required by law, such as Bahasa Indonesia and Pancasila. These additions do not change the core curriculum or qualification pathways.
  </p>

  <h3>What is the difference between SPK and bilingual or national-plus schools?</h3>
  <p>
    Bilingual and national-plus schools use the Indonesian national curriculum as their foundation, with international elements added on top. SPK schools use a foreign curriculum, such as the English National Curriculum or the IB, as the basis for all teaching and assessment.
  </p>

  <h3>Will attending an SPK school affect my child's ability to enter overseas schools or universities?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Quality SPK schools deliver fully recognised international qualifications and prepare pupils for global pathways. Admission outcomes depend on curriculum strength, not on the regulatory category.
  </p>

  <h3>How can parents assess the quality of an international school in Jakarta?</h3>
  <p>
    Look at curriculum integrity, teacher qualifications, accreditation or inspection evidence, leadership experience, and qualification outcomes. Licensing terms alone are not a reliable indicator of quality.
  </p>

  <h3>Why do fees vary so much between schools?</h3>
  <p>
    Fees reflect staffing costs, curriculum requirements, facilities, and the depth of international provision. Schools with experienced overseas teachers, established foreign curricula, and full accreditation typically have higher operating costs. Fee ranges across Jakarta's main international schools are covered in the <a href="/insights/international-school-fees-jakarta">international school fees guide</a>.
  </p>

